Text:
@nmemphis - For scanning, it won't matter whether you're using paperback or hardcover; it's the interior that counts. But a paperback would be easier to cut apart. If you're not going to take the book apart, I don't know, but maybe a paperback would lie flat more easily on a flatbed scanner.

If you ARE planning to scan something like this but haven't scanned other books, you might want to start with some smaller projects first. It'd be very frustrating to try to learn how to get the details right when every mistake means you'll have to redo 1000 pages!

And I'm glad you like the uploads. Thanks!

@Mertonoia - I'm glad to hear you have those recordings. I was wondering if you did ... but I don't really have the bandwidth to upload such large files myself without burdening my system for a long time.
